<div style="DISPLAY: block; TEXT-INDENT: 0pt">
<br></div>
<div style="DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 18pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="left"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman">The Company adopted the measurement date provisions of SFAS No. 158, "Employers' Accounting for Defined Benefit Pension and Other Postretirement Plans," effective January 1, 2008.&#160;&#160;The Company elected to utilize the alternate transition method to transition the measurement date for its defined pension benefit plan in Japan from
September 30 to December 31.&#160;&#160;Under this transition method, the Company charged 3/15ths of the estimated pension cost from October 1, 2007 to December 31, 2008 (or $0.8, net of taxes) to retained earnings as of January 1, 2008.</font></div>
<div style="DISPLAY: block; TEXT-INDENT: 0pt">
<br></div>
<div style="DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 18pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="left"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman">The Company maintains an irrevocable Rabbi trust to be held and invested in an unfunded arrangement for the payment of benefits to participants under certain defined benefit pension plans of the Company.&#160;&#160;At June 30, 2009, the accompanying condensed consolidated balance sheet included net assets of the trust (cash and cash equivalents
of $44, short term investments of $213 and long term investments of $23) that were restricted to the payment of pension benefits except under certain conditions, such as the Company's insolvency or termination of the trust.</font></div>
<div style="DISPLAY: block; TEXT-INDENT: 0pt">
<br></div>
<div id="PGBRK" style="MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt">
<div id="FTR">
<div id="GLFTR" style="WIDTH: 100%" align="left">&#160;</div></div>
<div id="PN" style="PAGE-BREAK-AFTER: always">
<div style="WIDTH: 100%; TEXT-ALIGN: center"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman">24</font></div>
<div style="WIDTH: 100%; TEXT-ALIGN: center"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-SIZE: 8pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman">&#160; </font></div></div>
<div id="HDR">
<div id="GLHDR" style="WIDTH: 100%" align="right">&#160;</div></div></div>
<div style="DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 27pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="left"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-WEIGHT: bold; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman">(14) Shareholders' Equity</font></div>
<div style="DISPLAY: block; TEXT-INDENT: 0pt">
<br></div>
<div>
<table cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" id="list" width="100%" style="FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: times new roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: times new roman">
<tr valign="top">
<td align="right" style="WIDTH: 54pt">
<div><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-STYLE: italic; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman">(a)&#160;&#160;</font></div></td>
<td>
<div style="MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="justify"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-STYLE: italic; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman">Share Cancellation</font></div></td></tr></table></div>
<div style="DISPLAY: block; TEXT-INDENT: 0pt">
<br></div>
<div style="DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 18pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="left"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman">On May 5, 2009, Alcon's shareholders approved the cancellation of 1,043,400 Alcon common shares, which the Company purchased during 2008.&#160;&#160;After the fulfillment of certain formal Swiss law requirements, the cancellation is expected to become effective in July or August 2009.</font></div>
<div style="DISPLAY: block; TEXT-INDENT: 0pt">
<br></div>
<div>
<table cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" id="list" width="100%" style="FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: times new roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: times new roman">
<tr valign="top">
<td align="right" style="WIDTH: 54pt">
<div><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-STYLE: italic; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman">(b)&#160;&#160;</font></div></td>
<td>
<div style="MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="justify"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-STYLE: italic; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman">Shareholder Agreement</font></div></td></tr></table></div>
<div style="DISPLAY: block; TEXT-INDENT: 0pt">
<br></div>
<div style="DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="left"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman"><font id="TAB1" style="MARGIN-LEFT: 14.4pt"></font>On April 6, 2008, Nestl&#233; and Novartis AG ("Novartis") executed the Purchase and Option Agreement pursuant to which Nestl&#233; agreed to sell approximately 74 million of its shares of Alcon common stock to Novartis in a cash transaction at a price of $143.18 per share.&#160;&#160;This
sale was consummated on July 7, 2008, and Novartis now owns a minority stake in Alcon of slightly less than 25% of Alcon's outstanding shares, while Nestl&#233; remains Alcon's majority shareholder with approximately 156 million Alcon shares comprising approximately 52% of the Company's outstanding shares.</font></div>
<div style="DISPLAY: block; TEXT-INDENT: 0pt">
<br></div>
<div style="DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="left"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman"><font id="TAB1" style="MARGIN-LEFT: 14.4pt"></font>The Purchase and Option Agreement between Nestl&#233; and Novartis also contains put and call option rights on the balance of approximately 156 million Alcon shares owned by Nestl&#233;.&#160;&#160;The option rights commence on January 1, 2010 and expire on July 31, 2011.&#160;&#160;As outlined
by the two parties, these rights grant (i) Novartis a call option to buy all but 4.1 million (or 2.5%) of Nestl&#233;'s remaining Alcon shares at a fixed price of $181 per share and the 4.1 million shares at the first stage price of $143.18 per share, and (ii) Nestl&#233; a put option to sell to Novartis all but 4.1 million of its remaining Alcon shares to Novartis at the lower of Novartis's call price of $181 per share or a 20.5% premium above the then-market price of Alcon shares, which will be calculated as
the average market price of Alcon shares during the five trading days immediately preceding the exercise date of the put option, with the 4.1 million share balance to be sold at the first stage closing price of $143.18 per share.</font></div>
<div style="DISPLAY: block; TEXT-INDENT: 0pt">
<br></div>
<div style="DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="left"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman"><font id="TAB1" style="MARGIN-LEFT: 14.4pt"></font>The consummation of a purchase and sale transaction under the Purchase and Option Agreement is subject to regulatory approvals.&#160;&#160;The consummation would trigger certain change of control provisions in the Company's share-based awards plan (including the vesting of certain outstanding
share-based awards), certain retirement plans for Company employees and other agreements.</font></div>
<div style="DISPLAY: block; TEXT-INDENT: 0pt">
<br></div>
<div style="DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 27pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="left"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-WEIGHT: bold; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman">(15) Commitments and Contingencies</font></div>
<div style="DISPLAY: block; TEXT-INDENT: 0pt">
<br></div>
<div style="DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 18pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="left"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman">Alcon, either alone or jointly with its commercial partners, has filed ten patent infringement actions against five different generic drug companies.&#160;&#160;With the exception of one Canadian generic challenger, all of these generic drug companies are seeking U.S. Food and Drug Administration ("FDA") approval to market generic versions
of Alcon products, under what is known as an Abbreviated New Drug Application ("ANDA").</font></div>
<div style="DISPLAY: block; TEXT-INDENT: 0pt">
<br></div>
<div style="DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 18pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="left"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman">The first infringement action was filed after Alcon received notice that Teva Pharmaceuticals USA, Inc. had filed an ANDA seeking approval to sell a generic version of Alcon's <font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-STYLE: italic">Vigamox</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-SIZE: 70%; VERTICAL-ALIGN: text-top">&#174;</font> antibiotic ophthalmic
solution.&#160;&#160;Moxifloxacin, the primary ingredient in <font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-STYLE: italic">Vigamox</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-SIZE: 70%; VERTICAL-ALIGN: text-top">&#174;</font>, is licensed to Alcon by Bayer HealthCare AG.&#160;&#160;As part of its ANDA, Teva challenged three patents covering Alcon's innovator product <font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-STYLE: italic">Vigamox</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-SIZE: 70%; VERTICAL-ALIGN: text-top">&#174;</font>. Two of the
patents are owned by Alcon's licensor, Bayer HealthCare AG, and the third, which expires in 2020, is owned by Alcon.&#160;&#160;The two Bayer HealthCare patents were also the subject of another Teva ANDA seeking approval to sell a generic version of Bayer HealthCare's systemic moxifloxacin product, Avelox<font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-SIZE: 70%; VERTICAL-ALIGN: text-top">&#174;</font>.&#160;&#160;Suit was filed by Alcon and Bayer HealthCare as co-plaintiffs against Teva relative to the <font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-STYLE: italic">Vigamox</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-SIZE: 70%; VERTICAL-ALIGN: text-top">&#174;</font> ANDA
on April 5, 2006 in the U.S. District Court in Delaware.&#160;&#160;Bayer HealthCare subsequently filed suit in the same court relative to the Avelox<font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-SIZE: 70%; VERTICAL-ALIGN: text-top">&#174;</font> ANDA, and the two suits were merged.&#160;&#160;Trial was scheduled to begin February 26, 2008, but the dispute between Bayer HealthCare and Teva relative to the two Bayer HealthCare patents was resolved by settlement on the eve of trial.&#160;&#160;Under the terms of the settlement,
Teva acknowledged the validity and enforceability of both Bayer HealthCare patents, and further acknowledged that its proposed generic ophthalmic product would infringe both patents.&#160;&#160;Teva has therefore relinquished any claim that it is</font></div>
<div style="DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 18pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="left"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman">&#160;</font></div>
<div id="PGBRK" style="MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt">
<div id="FTR">
<div id="GLFTR" style="WIDTH: 100%" align="left">&#160;</div></div>
<div id="PN" style="PAGE-BREAK-AFTER: always">
<div style="WIDTH: 100%; TEXT-ALIGN: center"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman">25</font></div>
<div style="WIDTH: 100%; TEXT-ALIGN: center"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-SIZE: 8pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman">&#160; </font></div></div>
<div id="HDR">
<div id="GLHDR" style="WIDTH: 100%" align="right">&#160;</div><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman">entitled to market the generic ophthalmic product prior to September 4, 2014.&#160;&#160;Alcon remains the exclusive ophthalmic licensee under the Bayer HealthCare patents.&#160;&#160;The trial relative to the Alcon patent began on February 28, 2008 and concluded on March 6, 2008.&#160;&#160;Judgment is not expected until the second half of 2009.&#160;&#160;Should Teva succeed in
overcoming the Alcon patent and secure FDA approval, it would be entitled to sell a generic moxifloxacin product that would compete with Alcon's <font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-STYLE: italic">Vigamox</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-SIZE: 70%; VERTICAL-ALIGN: text-top">&#174;</font> product in the United States on September 4, 2014, well before the 2020 expiration of the Alcon patent.&#160;&#160;Such competition would be expected to impact significantly the Company's sales and profits.</font></div></div>
<div style="DISPLAY: block; TEXT-INDENT: 0pt">
<br></div>
<div style="DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 18pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="left"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman">The second patent infringement action was filed after Alcon received notice that Apotex, a Canadian-based generic drug company, had filed an ANDA challenging one of the patents covering Alcon's <font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-STYLE: italic">Patanol</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-SIZE: 70%; VERTICAL-ALIGN: text-top">&#174;</font> anti-allergy
eye product.&#160;&#160;Alcon's raw material supplier, Kyowa Hakko Kirin Co., Ltd., holds another U.S. patent that has not been challenged in this case and expires on December 18, 2010.&#160;&#160;The patent that Apotex has challenged, which is co-owned by Alcon and Kyowa, will expire in 2015.&#160;&#160;Alcon and Kyowa, as co-plaintiffs, filed suit against Apotex Inc. and Apotex Corp. on November 15, 2006 in the U.S. District Court in Indianapolis, Indiana.&#160;&#160;As a result of the lawsuit filing, the FDA
must delay any approval of the Apotex ANDA for 30 months unless the litigation is earlier resolved or the court modifies the 30-month stay on FDA approval.&#160;&#160;Trial was scheduled for July 27, 2009, but on July 13, 2009, the Court vacated the trial date and indicated that a new trial date would be set by a separate order.&#160;&#160;Should Apotex succeed in overcoming the challenged patent and secure FDA approval, it would not be entitled to begin selling a generic olopatadine product that would compete
with Alcon's <font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-STYLE: italic">Patanol</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-SIZE: 70%; VERTICAL-ALIGN: text-top">&#174;</font> product in the United States until December 18, 2010.&#160;&#160;Such competition would be expected to impact significantly the Company's sales and profits.</font></div>
<div style="DISPLAY: block; TEXT-INDENT: 0pt">
<br></div>
<div style="DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 18pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="left"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman">The third patent infringement action was filed after Alcon received notice on October 1, 2007 that Barr Laboratories, Inc. had filed an ANDA challenging the patents underlying Alcon's <font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-STYLE: italic">Patanol</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-SIZE: 70%; VERTICAL-ALIGN: text-top">&#174;</font> product.&#160;&#160;Unlike
the Apotex ANDA described above, which is challenging only the patent jointly owned by Kyowa and Alcon, the Barr ANDA is also challenging Kyowa's composition patent on olopatadine, the active agent in <font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-STYLE: italic">Patanol</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-SIZE: 70%; VERTICAL-ALIGN: text-top">&#174;</font>.&#160;&#160;Alcon and Kyowa filed suit in the Federal District Court in Indianapolis (where the Apotex case is pending) on October 23, 2007.&#160;&#160;As a result
of the lawsuit filing, the FDA must delay any approval of the Barr ANDA for 30 months unless the litigation is earlier resolved or the court modifies the 30-month stay on FDA approval.&#160;&#160;The 30-month period after which the FDA could approve Barr&#8217;s generic product will expire at the end of March 2010, nine months before the Kyowa composition patent expires.&#160;&#160;Trial is currently scheduled for late April 2010.&#160;&#160;Should Barr succeed in overcoming both of the challenged patents and
secure FDA approval, it and Apotex may be entitled to begin selling a generic olopatadine product that would compete with Alcon's <font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-STYLE: italic">Patanol</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-SIZE: 70%; VERTICAL-ALIGN: text-top">&#174;</font> product in the United States prior to December 18, 2010.&#160;&#160;Such competition would be expected to impact significantly the Company's sales and profits.</font></div>
<div style="DISPLAY: block; TEXT-INDENT: 0pt">
<br></div>
<div style="DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 18pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="left"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman">The fourth patent infringement action was filed after Alcon received notice in late November 2008 that Barr Laboratories, Inc. had filed an ANDA challenging the patents underlying Alcon&#8217;s <font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-STYLE: italic">Pataday</font>&#8482; once daily olopatadine product.&#160;&#160;The Barr ANDA is challenging the
patent jointly owned by Kyowa and Alcon (described above), as well as two later issued patents owned by Alcon that cover the <font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-STYLE: italic">Pataday</font>&#8482; formulation.&#160;&#160;Of the two Alcon patents, the latest expiry date is November 2023.&#160;&#160;Barr is not challenging the Kyowa patent on olopatadine that expires in December 2010.&#160;&#160;&#160;Alcon and Kyowa filed suit in the Federal District Court in Indianapolis (where the Apotex and Barr <font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-STYLE: italic">Patanol</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-SIZE: 70%; VERTICAL-ALIGN: text-top; FONT-STYLE: italic">&#174;</font> product
cases are pending) on January 8, 2009.&#160;&#160;As a result of the lawsuit filing, the FDA must delay any approval of the Barr ANDA for 30 months unless the litigation is earlier resolved or the court modifies the 30-month stay on FDA approval.&#160;&#160;The 30-month period after which the FDA could approve Barr&#8217;s generic product should expire in May 2011.&#160;&#160;Trial has not yet been scheduled in this case.&#160;&#160;If Barr succeeds in overcoming all of the challenged patents and secures FDA
approval, it would be entitled to begin selling a generic olopatadine product that would compete with Alcon&#8217;s <font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-STYLE: italic">Pataday</font>&#8482; product in the United States on December 18, 2010.&#160;&#160;Such competition would be expected to impact significantly the Company's sales and profits.</font></div>
<div style="DISPLAY: block; TEXT-INDENT: 0pt">
<br></div>
<div style="DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 18pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="left"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman">The fifth and sixth ANDA patent suits were filed February 2, 2009 in the U.S. District Court in Indianapolis against Apotex and Sandoz respectively.</font></div>
<div style="DISPLAY: block; TEXT-INDENT: 0pt">
<br></div>
<div id="PGBRK" style="MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt">
<div id="FTR">
<div id="GLFTR" style="WIDTH: 100%" align="left">&#160;</div></div>
<div id="PN" style="PAGE-BREAK-AFTER: always">
<div style="WIDTH: 100%; TEXT-ALIGN: center"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman">26</font></div>
<div style="WIDTH: 100%; TEXT-ALIGN: center"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-SIZE: 8pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman">&#160; </font></div></div>
<div id="HDR">
<div id="GLHDR" style="WIDTH: 100%" align="right">&#160;</div></div></div>
<div style="DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 18pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="left"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman">Alcon received notice January 12, 2009, that Apotex has followed Barr in filing an ANDA challenging the patents underlying Alcon&#8217;s <font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-STYLE: italic">Pataday</font>&#8482; once daily olopatadine product.&#160;&#160;Like Barr's ANDA, the Apotex ANDA is challenging the patent jointly owned by Kyowa and Alcon
(described above), as well as two later issued patents owned by Alcon that cover the <font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-STYLE: italic">Pataday</font>&#8482; formulation.&#160;&#160;Apotex is not challenging the Kyowa patent on olopatadine that expires in December 2010.&#160;&#160;Because the suit was filed within the statutory 45-day period, the FDA must delay any approval of the Apotex ANDA until June 2011, unless the litigation is earlier resolved or the court modifies the 30-month stay on FDA approval.&#160;&#160;Trial
has not yet been scheduled in this case.&#160;&#160;If Apotex succeeds in overcoming both of the challenged patents and secures FDA approval, and after the expiration of Barr's potential 180-day "first filer" exclusivity period, it would be entitled to begin selling a generic olopatadine product that would compete with Alcon&#8217;s <font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-STYLE: italic">Pataday</font>&#8482; product in the United States in April 2011.&#160;&#160;Such competition would be expected to impact the Company's
sales and profits.</font></div>
<div style="DISPLAY: block; TEXT-INDENT: 0pt">
<br></div>
<div style="DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 18pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="left"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman">Alcon received notice on January 15, 2009 that Sandoz Inc. (an affiliate of Novartis) has filed an ANDA challenging one of the patents underlying Alcon&#8217;s <font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-STYLE: italic">Patanol</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-SIZE: 70%; VERTICAL-ALIGN: text-top">&#174;</font> product.&#160;&#160;Similar to
the Apotex ANDA on <font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-STYLE: italic">Patanol</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-SIZE: 70%; VERTICAL-ALIGN: text-top">&#174;</font>, the Sandoz ANDA is challenging only the patent jointly owned by Kyowa and Alcon, but not the Kyowa-owned patent on olopatadine, which expires December 2010.&#160;&#160;Because the suit was filed within the statutory 45-day period, the FDA must delay any approval of the Sandoz ANDA until June 2011 unless the litigation is earlier resolved or the
court modifies the 30-month stay on FDA approval.&#160;&#160;However, as a third ANDA filer (behind both Apotex and Barr), Sandoz would not be entitled to receive FDA approval until the expiration or forfeiture of a 180-day exclusivity period that would be granted to Apotex (the first filer) if it were successful in its patent challenge.&#160;&#160;Trial has not yet been scheduled in this case and consolidation with the above-described Barr (<font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-STYLE: italic">Patanol</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-SIZE: 70%; VERTICAL-ALIGN: text-top; FONT-STYLE: italic">&#174;</font>)
suit has been requested.&#160;&#160;Subject to the possibility of the 180-day exclusivity period that could accrue to Apotex, if Sandoz succeeds in overcoming the challenged patent and secures FDA approval, it would be entitled to begin selling a generic olopatadine product that would compete with Alcon&#8217;s <font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-STYLE: italic">Patanol</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-SIZE: 70%; VERTICAL-ALIGN: text-top">&#174;</font> product in the United States in April 2011.&#160;&#160;Such
competition would be expected to impact significantly the Company's sales and profits.</font></div>
<div style="DISPLAY: block; TEXT-INDENT: 0pt">
<br></div>
<div style="DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 18pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="left"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman">By letter dated March 17, 2009, Alcon received notice that Barr Laboratories, Inc. has filed a Paragraph IV certification with its ANDA for a generic version of Alcon's <font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-STYLE: italic">TRAVATAN</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-SIZE: 70%; VERTICAL-ALIGN: text-top">&#174;</font> product containing 0.004%
travoprost.&#160;&#160;Barr is challenging the following patents listed in the Orange Book for <font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-STYLE: italic">TRAVATAN</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-SIZE: 70%; VERTICAL-ALIGN: text-top">&#174;</font>: U.S. Patent Nos. 5,510,383; 5,631,287; 5,849,792; 5,889,052; and 6,011,062.&#160;&#160;With the exception of the '383 patent, which expires in 2013, all of the patents will expire in December 2014.&#160;&#160;Alcon filed suit against Barr in the U.S. District Court in
Delaware on April 30, 2009 and thereby secured the statutory 30-month stay on FDA approval of the generic product.&#160;&#160;The FDA must delay any approval of the Barr ANDA until September 2011, unless the litigation is earlier resolved or the court modifies the 30-month stay on FDA approval.&#160;&#160;Trial has not yet been scheduled in this case.&#160;&#160;Should Barr succeed in overcoming all of the challenged patents and secure FDA approval, it would be entitled to begin selling a generic travoprost product
that would compete with Alcon&#8217;s <font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-STYLE: italic">TRAVATAN</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-SIZE: 70%; VERTICAL-ALIGN: text-top">&#174;</font> product in the United States.&#160;&#160;Such competition would be expected to impact significantly the Company's sales and profits.</font></div>
<div style="DISPLAY: block; TEXT-INDENT: 0pt">
<br></div>
<div style="DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 18pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="left"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman">By letter dated April 9, 2009, Sandoz Canada Inc. (an affiliate of Novartis) notified Alcon Canada that Sandoz has filed an Abbreviated New Drug Submission (ANDS) seeking approval from the Canadian Minister of Health to market a generic version of Alcon's <font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-STYLE: italic">Patanol</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-SIZE: 70%; VERTICAL-ALIGN: text-top">&#174;</font> product.&#160;&#160;The
Sandoz ANDS is challenging only one of the two patents listed in the Canadian Patent Register for the <font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-STYLE: italic">Patanol</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-SIZE: 70%; VERTICAL-ALIGN: text-top">&#174;</font> product.&#160;&#160;The challenged patent (Canadian Patent No. 2,195,094) is jointly owned by Kyowa and Alcon and expires in May 2016.&#160;&#160;Alcon and Kyowa filed suit on May 25, 2009 in the Federal Court in Toronto, thereby securing a 24-month delay in the
regulatory approval from the Minister of Health, which can only be shortened if the litigation is earlier resolved or the court modifies the 24-month stay on such approval.&#160;&#160;Should Sandoz succeed in overcoming the challenged patent and secure Minister of Health approval, it would be entitled to begin selling a generic olopatadine product that would compete with Alcon&#8217;s <font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-STYLE: italic">Patanol</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-SIZE: 70%; VERTICAL-ALIGN: text-top">&#174;</font> product
in Canada well before the patent expiration in 2016, but not before expiration of the unchallenged patent in November 2012.&#160;&#160;Such competition would be expected to impact the Company's sales and profits.</font></div>
<div style="DISPLAY: block; TEXT-INDENT: 0pt">
<br></div>
<div style="DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 18pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="left"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman">By letter dated June 1, 2009, Alcon received notice that Par Pharmaceutical, Inc. has filed a Paragraph IV certification with its ANDAs for a generic version of Alcon&#8217;s <font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-STYLE: italic">TRAVATAN</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-SIZE: 70%; VERTICAL-ALIGN: text-top; FONT-STYLE: italic">&#174;</font> and <font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-STYLE: italic">TRAVATAN
Z</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-SIZE: 70%; VERTICAL-ALIGN: text-top; FONT-STYLE: italic">&#174;</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-STYLE: italic">&#160;</font>products.&#160;&#160;Par is </font></div>
<div style="DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 18pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="left"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman">&#160;</font></div>
<div id="PGBRK" style="MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt">

<div id="GLHDR" style="WIDTH: 100%" align="right">&#160;</div><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman">challenging the following patents listed in the Orange Book for <font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-STYLE: italic">TRAVATAN</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-SIZE: 70%; VERTICAL-ALIGN: text-top; FONT-STYLE: italic">&#174;</font> and <font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-STYLE: italic">TRAVATAN Z</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-SIZE: 70%; VERTICAL-ALIGN: text-top; FONT-STYLE: italic">&#174;</font>:&#160;&#160;U.S.
Patent Nos. 5,510,383; 5,631,287; 5,849,792; 5,889,052; 6,011,062; 6,503,497; and 6,849,253.&#160;&#160;All of these patents will expire by the end of 2014.&#160;&#160;On July 1, 2009, Alcon filed suit in the U.S. District Court in Delaware, thereby securing a statutory stay under which the FDA must delay any approval of the Par ANDAs until December 2011, unless the litigation is earlier resolved or the court modifies the 30-month stay on FDA approval.&#160;&#160;Trial has not yet been scheduled in this case
and consolidation with the above-described Barr (<font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-STYLE: italic">TRAVATAN</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-SIZE: 70%; VERTICAL-ALIGN: text-top; FONT-STYLE: italic">&#174;</font>) suit has been requested.&#160;&#160;Subject to the possibility of the 180-day exclusivity period that could accrue to Barr (as first filer) relative to the <font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-STYLE: italic">TRAVATAN</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-SIZE: 70%; VERTICAL-ALIGN: text-top; FONT-STYLE: italic">&#174;</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-STYLE: italic">&#160;</font>product,
if Par succeeds in overcoming all of the challenged patents and secures FDA approval, it would be entitled to begin selling generic travoprost products that would compete with Alcon&#8217;s<font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-SIZE: 70%; VERTICAL-ALIGN: text-top; FONT-STYLE: italic">&#160;</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-STYLE: italic">TRAVATAN</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-SIZE: 70%; VERTICAL-ALIGN: text-top; FONT-STYLE: italic"> &#174;</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-STYLE: italic">&#160;</font>and <font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-STYLE: italic">TRAVATAN

<div style="DISPLAY: block; TEXT-INDENT: 0pt">
<br></div>
<div style="DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 18pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="left"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman">By letter dated June 24, 2009, Alcon received notice that Barr Laboratories, Inc. has filed a Paragraph IV certification with its ANDA for a generic version of Alcon&#8217;s <font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-STYLE: italic">TRAVATAN Z</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-SIZE: 70%; VERTICAL-ALIGN: text-top; FONT-STYLE: italic">&#174;</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-SIZE: 70%; VERTICAL-ALIGN: text-top">&#160;</font>product.&#160;&#160;Barr
is challenging the following patents listed in the Orange Book for <font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-STYLE: italic">TRAVATAN Z</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-SIZE: 70%; VERTICAL-ALIGN: text-top; FONT-STYLE: italic">&#174;</font>:&#160;&#160;U.S. Patent Nos. 5,510,383; 5,889,052; 6,503,497; and 6,849,253.&#160;&#160;All of the patents will expire by the end of 2014.&#160;&#160;On July 13, 2009, Alcon filed suit in the U.S. District Court in Delaware, thereby securing a statutory stay under which the
FDA must delay any approval of the Barr ANDA until December 2011, unless the litigation is earlier resolved or the court modifies the 30-month stay on FDA approval.&#160;&#160;Trial has not yet been scheduled in this case, and a request for consolidation with the above-described Barr (<font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-STYLE: italic">TRAVATAN</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-SIZE: 70%; VERTICAL-ALIGN: text-top; FONT-STYLE: italic">&#174;</font>) and Par (<font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-STYLE: italic">TRAVATAN</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-SIZE: 70%; VERTICAL-ALIGN: text-top; FONT-STYLE: italic">&#174;</font> and <font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-STYLE: italic">TRAVATAN
Z</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-SIZE: 70%; VERTICAL-ALIGN: text-top; FONT-STYLE: italic">&#174;</font>) suits is being considered.&#160;&#160;Subject to the possibility of the 180-day exclusivity period that could accrue to Par (as first filer) relative to the <font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-STYLE: italic">TRAVATAN Z</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-SIZE: 70%; VERTICAL-ALIGN: text-top; FONT-STYLE: italic">&#174;</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-SIZE: 70%; VERTICAL-ALIGN: text-top">&#160;</font>product,
if Barr succeeds in overcoming all of the challenged patents and secures FDA approval, it would be entitled to begin selling a generic travoprost product that would compete with Alcon&#8217;s <font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-STYLE: italic">TRAVATAN Z</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-SIZE: 70%; VERTICAL-ALIGN: text-top; FONT-STYLE: italic">&#174;</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-SIZE: 70%; VERTICAL-ALIGN: text-top">&#160;</font>product in the United States in December 2011.&#160;&#160;Such competition
would be expected to impact significantly the Company&#8217;s sales and profits.</font></div>
<div style="DISPLAY: block; TEXT-INDENT: 0pt">
<br></div>
<div style="DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 18pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="left"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman">In April 16, 2008, Synergetics USA, Inc., a microsurgical device company, filed a civil antitrust lawsuit in the U.S. District Court for the Southern District of New York against the Company and its subsidiary, Alcon Laboratories, Inc.&#160;&#160;Synergetics asserts that it has suffered losses resulting from alleged unlawful/unfair practices
and seeks a recovery that it claims could exceed $100.&#160;&#160;Synergetics alleges that Alcon has used monopoly power in the market for vitreoretinal surgical equipment to control purchasing decisions in favor of its surgical illumination sources and associated accessories, and that Alcon has done this to the detriment of sales of Synergetics's products, particularly its line of light sources, light pipes and other accessories.&#160;&#160;Synergetics also asserts that Alcon engaged in allegedly anti-competitive
behaviors.&#160;&#160;While there can be no assurance that an adverse outcome in the case cannot occur, the Company believes that the Synergetics claims are without merit.&#160;&#160;On June 23, 2008, the Company filed its answer and counterclaim in the District Court.&#160;&#160;Synergetics subsequently amended its original Complaint, and on October 14, 2008, the Company filed its Motion to Dismiss Synergetics's First Amended Complaint.&#160;&#160;On February 12, 2009, Synergetics filed a Motion for Summary
Judgment relative to the Company&#8217;s counterclaims.&#160;&#160;On February 23, 2009, the court granted the Company&#8217;s Motions to Dismiss based on Synergetics&#8217;s failure to properly plead its claims.&#160;&#160;On March 6, 2009, Synergetics filed a Second Amended Complaint.&#160;&#160;The Company then filed another Motion to Dismiss directed to the Second Amended Complaint.&#160;&#160;That motion was granted in-part and denied in-part on June 4, 2009.&#160;&#160;On July 9, 2009, the Court granted
Synergetics&#8217;s Motion for Summary Judgment on the Company&#8217;s counterclaims.&#160;&#160;The Company intends to vigorously defend itself in the case.&#160;&#160;A trial date in 2010 is expected but has not yet been scheduled by the court.</font></div>
<div style="DISPLAY: block; TEXT-INDENT: 0pt">
<br></div>
<div style="DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 18pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="left"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman">A subsidiary of the Company, Alcon Research, Ltd., filed a Complaint on October 9, 2008 against Synergetics USA, Inc. for patent infringement of U.S. Patent No. 5,603,710, entitled, "Laser Delivery System with Soft Tip."&#160;&#160;The suit was filed in the U.S. District Court for the Northern District of Texas in Fort Worth.&#160;&#160;The
Complaint asserts that Synergetics has knowingly and willfully infringed the Company's patent, which is directed to ophthalmic laser delivery systems having a probe with a soft tip.&#160;&#160;In addition to seeking actual and exemplary monetary damages relating to the willful patent infringement and injunctive relief to prevent Synergetics from continuing its infringement of the patent, the Company is requesting that the District Court award the Company its attorneys' fees and costs.&#160;&#160;Synergetics has
answered the Complaint and counterclaimed for a declaratory judgment of non-infringement and </font></div>
<div style="DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 18pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="left"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman">&#160;</font></div>
<div id="PGBRK" style="MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt">
<div id="FTR">
<div id="GLFTR" style="WIDTH: 100%" align="left">&#160;</div></div>
<div id="PN" style="PAGE-BREAK-AFTER: always">
<div style="WIDTH: 100%; TEXT-ALIGN: center"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman">28</font></div>
<div style="WIDTH: 100%; TEXT-ALIGN: center"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-SIZE: 8pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman">&#160; </font></div></div>
<div id="HDR">
<div id="GLHDR" style="WIDTH: 100%" align="right">&#160;</div><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman">patent invalidity.&#160;&#160;No trial date has been set.&#160;&#160;An adverse ruling by the court, while possible, would not be expected to impact significantly the Company's sales and profits.</font></div></div>
<div style="DISPLAY: block; TEXT-INDENT: 0pt">
<br></div>
<div style="DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 18pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="left"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman">On February 25, 2009, the Company, together with subsidiaries Alcon Laboratories, Inc. and Alcon Research, Ltd., filed a second suit against Synergetics in the U.S. District Court in Fort Worth.&#160;&#160;This case alleges infringement of Alcon's U.S. Patent 5,318,560 directed to aspirating laser probes, as well as trademark infringement
and unfair competition relating to Synergetics's unauthorized use of Alcon's marks (<font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-STYLE: italic">ALCON</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-SIZE: 70%; VERTICAL-ALIGN: text-top">&#174;</font>, <font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-STYLE: italic">Accurus</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-SIZE: 70%; VERTICAL-ALIGN: text-top">&#174;</font>, and <font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-STYLE: italic">Grieshaber</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-SIZE: 70%; VERTICAL-ALIGN: text-top">&#174;</font>)
on its website.&#160;&#160;On March 20, 2009, these claims were added to an amended complaint in the '710 patent suit described immediately above, effectively merging the two suits.&#160;&#160;An adverse ruling by the court, while possible, would not be expected to impact significantly the Company's sales and profits.&#160;&#160;Synergetics has requested that the U.S. Patent and Trademark Office reexamine both patents-in-suit and has filed a motion to stay the litigation pending a decision by the Patent Office.&#160;&#160;The
court has not ruled on that motion.</font></div>
<div style="DISPLAY: block; TEXT-INDENT: 0pt">
<br></div>
<div style="DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 18pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="left"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman">On December 18, 2008, James M. Nielsen, M.D. filed a patent infringement suit against Alcon, Inc. and Alcon Laboratories, Inc. in the U.S. District Court for the Northern District of Texas in Dallas.&#160;&#160;Dr. Nielsen is asserting that his U.S. Patent No. 5,158,572 entitled "Multifocal Intraocular Lens" is being infringed by the Company&#8217;s <font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-STYLE: italic">ReSTOR</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-SIZE: 70%; VERTICAL-ALIGN: text-top">&#174;</font>,<font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-STYLE: italic">&#160;</font>intraocular
lens.&#160;&#160;The patent, which expires at the end of October 2009, was previously licensed to Advanced Medical Optics, Inc.&#160;&#160;Alcon filed its Answer January 12, 2009.&#160;&#160;The Answer includes a counterclaim for a declaratory judgment that the patent-in-suit is invalid and not infringed.&#160;&#160;No trial date has been set.</font></div>
<div style="DISPLAY: block; TEXT-INDENT: 0pt">
<br></div>
<div style="DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 18pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="left"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman">On January 22, 2009, Elan Pharma International Ltd. sued two of the Company's subsidiaries, Alcon Laboratories, Inc. and Alcon Manufacturing, Ltd., in the U.S. District Court for the Eastern District of Texas in Sherman, alleging infringement of two Elan patents on nanoparticle technology (U.S. Patent Nos. 5,298,262 and 5,429,842).&#160;&#160;The
complaint claims that the Company's <font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-STYLE: italic">Azopt</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-SIZE: 70%; VERTICAL-ALIGN: text-top; FONT-STYLE: italic">&#174;</font>,&#160;&#160;product and, potentially, other products infringe the two patents.&#160;&#160;The Company answered and counterclaimed on May 12, 2009.&#160;&#160;Elan then moved to dismiss certain of the Company&#8217;s affirmative defenses and counterclaims.&#160;&#160;The Company has filed an amended answer and
counterclaims providing greater detail with respect to the Company&#8217;s inequitable conduct counterclaims.&#160;&#160;The Company believes that it has strong defenses and intends to defend itself vigorously.</font></div>
<div style="DISPLAY: block; TEXT-INDENT: 0pt">
<br></div>
<div style="DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 18pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="left"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman">The Company and its subsidiaries are parties to a variety of other legal proceedings arising out of the ordinary course of business, including proceedings relating to product liability and patent infringement.&#160;&#160;The Company believes that it has valid defenses and is vigorously defending the litigation pending against it.</font></div>
<div style="DISPLAY: block; TEXT-INDENT: 0pt">
<br></div>
<div style="DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 18pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="left"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman">While the results of the aforementioned contingencies cannot be predicted with certainty, management believes that the ultimate liability, if any, will not have a material adverse effect on the Company's consolidated financial position or results of operations.&#160;&#160;Litigation contingencies are subject to change based on settlements
and court decisions.</font></div>
<div style="DISPLAY: block; TEXT-INDENT: 0pt">
<br></div>
<div style="DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 18pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="left"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman">The Company may be subject to future litigation and infringement claims, which could cause the Company to incur significant expenses or prevent the Company from selling its products.&#160;&#160;The Company operates in an industry susceptible to significant product liability claims.&#160;&#160;Product liability claims may be asserted against
the Company in the future arising out of events not known to the Company at the present time.</font></div>
<div style="DISPLAY: block; TEXT-INDENT: 0pt">
<br></div>
<div style="DISPLAY: block; TEXT-INDENT: 0pt">
<br></div>
<div style="DISPLAY: block; TEXT-INDENT: 0pt">
<br></div>

<div id="HDR">
<div id="GLHDR" style="WIDTH: 100%" align="right"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-SIZE: 8pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman">&#160; </font></div></div></div>

<div>
<table align="center" border="0" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" id="hangingindent" width="100%" style="FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: times new roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: times new roman">
<tr valign="top">
<td style="WIDTH: 45pt">
<div><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman">&#160; </font></div></td>
<td>
<div align="left"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-WEIGHT: bold; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman">ITEM 2.MANAGEMENT'S DISCUSSION AND ANALYSIS OF FINANCIAL CONDITION AND RESULTS OF OPERATIONS</font></div></td></tr></table></div>
<div style="DISPLAY: block; TEXT-INDENT: 0pt">
<br></div>
<div style="DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="justify"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-WEIGHT: bold; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman">Results of Operations</font></div>
<div style="DISPLAY: block; TEXT-INDENT: 0pt">
<br></div>
<div style="DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="justify"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-WEIGHT: bold; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman">Three months ended June 30, 2009 compared to three months ended June 30, 2008</font></div>
<div style="DISPLAY: block; TEXT-INDENT: 0pt">
<br></div>
<div style="DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="left"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman"><font id="TAB1" style="MARGIN-LEFT: 14.4pt"></font>The following discussion compares operations for the three months ended June 30, 2009 to operations for the three months ended June 30, 2008.</font></div>
<div style="DISPLAY: block; TEXT-INDENT: 0pt">
<br></div>
<div style="DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="left"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-WEIGHT: bold; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-STYLE: italic; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman">Sales</font></div>
<div style="DISPLAY: block; TEXT-INDENT: 0pt">
<br></div>
<div style="DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="left"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman"><font id="TAB1" style="MARGIN-LEFT: 14.4pt"></font>The Company's global sales decreased 3.4% to $1,677 million for the three months ended June 30, 2009 from the same period in 2008.&#160;&#160;The effect of unfavorable exchange rates decreased global sales 6.7%.&#160;&#160;Excluding the effect of foreign exchange fluctuations, global sales
would have grown 3.3%, primarily reflecting volume growth during the three months ended June 30, 2009.</font></div>
<div style="DISPLAY: block; TEXT-INDENT: 0pt">
<br></div>

<div style="DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="right"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-WEIGHT: bold; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: times new roman">(3.4</font></div></td>
<td align="left" valign="top" width="2%">
<div style="DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="left"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-WEIGHT: bold; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: times new roman">)</font></div></td>
<td valign="top" width="1%"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: times new roman">&#160; </font></td>
<td align="right" valign="top" width="7%">
<div style="DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="right"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-WEIGHT: bold; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: times new roman">(6.7</font></div></td>
<td align="left" valign="top" width="2%">
<div style="DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="left"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-WEIGHT: bold; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: times new roman">)</font></div></td>
<td valign="top" width="1%"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: times new roman">&#160; </font></td>
<td align="right" valign="top" width="8%">
<div style="DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="right"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-WEIGHT: bold; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: times new roman">3.3</font></div></td>
<td valign="top" width="2%"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: times new roman">&#160; </font></td>
<td valign="top" width="2%"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: times new roman">&#160; </font></td></tr></table></div>
<div style="DISPLAY: block; TEXT-INDENT: 0pt">
<br></div>
<div>
<table cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" id="list" width="100%" style="FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: times new roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: times new roman">
<tr valign="top">
<td align="right" style="WIDTH: 36pt">
<div><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman">(a)&#160;&#160;</font></div></td>
<td>
<div style="MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="justify"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman">Change in constant currency (as referenced throughout this discussion) is determined by comparing adjusted 2009 reported amounts, calculated using 2008 monthly average exchange rates, to the actual 2008 reported amounts.&#160;&#160;Sales change in constant currency is not a U.S. GAAP defined measure of revenue growth.&#160;&#160;Change in constant currency
calculates sales growth without the impact of foreign exchange fluctuations.&#160;&#160;Management believes constant currency sales growth is an important measure of the Company&#8217;s operations because it provides investors with a clearer picture of the core rate of sales growth attributable to changes in unit volumes and local currency prices.&#160;&#160;Sales change in constant currency, as defined and presented by the Company, may not be comparable to similar measures reported by other companies.</font></div></td></tr></table></div>
<div style="DISPLAY: block; TEXT-INDENT: 0pt">
<br></div>
<div style="DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="left"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman"><font id="TAB1" style="MARGIN-LEFT: 18pt"></font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-SIZE: 10pt">Alcon United States sales improved 0.3% to $790 million for the three months ended June 30, 2009, from $788 million for the comparable period in 2008.&#160;&#160;This improvement was driven by sales increases for advanced technology intraocular
lenses, other cataract and vitreoretinal products, pharmaceuticals to treat glaucoma and infections, and over-the-counter artificial tears eye drops.&#160;&#160;These increases were partially offset by generic competition to </font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-STYLE: italic">TobraDex</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-SIZE: 70%; VERTICAL-ALIGN: text-top">&#174;</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-SIZE: 10pt"> suspension, changes in wholesaler purchasing patterns for pharmaceutical
products and changes in retailer purchasing patterns in contact lens care products.</font></font></div>
<div style="DISPLAY: block; TEXT-INDENT: 0pt">
<br></div>
<div id="PGBRK" style="MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt">
<div id="FTR">
<div id="GLFTR" style="WIDTH: 100%" align="left">&#160;</div></div>
<div id="PN" style="PAGE-BREAK-AFTER: always">
<div style="WIDTH: 100%; TEXT-ALIGN: center"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman">30</font></div>
<div style="WIDTH: 100%; TEXT-ALIGN: center"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-SIZE: 8pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman">&#160; </font></div></div>
<div id="HDR">
<div id="GLHDR" style="WIDTH: 100%" align="right">&#160;</div></div></div>
<div style="DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="left"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman"><font id="TAB1" style="MARGIN-LEFT: 18pt"></font>Alcon International sales decreased 6.4% to $887 million in the three months ended June 30, 2009, from $948 million in the same period of 2008.&#160;&#160;The effect of unfavorable exchange rates decreased Alcon International sales 12.3%.&#160;&#160;Excluding the effect of foreign exchange fluctuations,
Alcon International sales would have grown 5.9%, primarily reflecting volume growth during the period.&#160;&#160;Sales growth of our glaucoma products and the organic sales growth in emerging markets were the main contributors to this performance.</font></div>
<div style="DISPLAY: block; TEXT-INDENT: 0pt">

<td align="right" valign="top" width="7%">
